g.text: {} 87_No Filter: Cultural and Socioeconomic Diversity in Contrastive Vision-Language Models
We study cultural and socioeconomic diversity in contrastive vision-language models (VLMs). Using a
broad range of benchmark datasets and evaluation metrics, we bring to attention several important
'No Filter: Cultural and Socioeconomic Diversity in Contrastive Vision-Language Models'
findings. First, the common filtering of training data to English image-text pairs disadvantages
communities of lower socioeconomic status and negatively impacts cultural understanding. Notably, this
'We study cultural and socioeconomic diversity in contrastive vision-language models
performance gap is not captured by - and even at odds with - the currently popular evaluation metrics
derived from the Western-centric ImageNet and COCO datasets. Second, pretraining with global,
unfiltered data before fine-tuning on English content can improve cultural understanding without
sacrificing performance on said popular benchmarks. Third, we introduce the task of geo-localization
as a novel evaluation metric to assess cultural diversity in VLMs. Our work underscores the value of
using diverse data to create more inclusive multimodal systems and lays the groundwork for developing
VLMs that better represent global perspectives.
